Produce, in a single call, the main relevant graphical views of alpha- and
beta-diversity for a phyloseq object as a function of \strong{one} sample
variable (\code{fact}). The set of panels adapts to the \emph{type} of \code{fact}:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Numeric variable} — alpha-diversity is shown as a Hill-numbers scatter
plot against the variable (via \code{\link[=ggscatt_pq]{ggscatt_pq()}}, one panel per Hill order
\code{q}, with the correlation statistics from \pkg{ggstatsplot}); the
ordination and UMAP points are colored by a continuous gradient. Venn/UpSet
panels are skipped (they require discrete groups).
\item \strong{Factor with 2 to \code{venn_max} levels} — alpha-diversity bar plots with
error bars and Tukey letters (via \code{\link[=hill_bar_pq]{hill_bar_pq()}}), a Venn diagram of
shared taxa (via \code{\link[=ggvenn_pq]{ggvenn_pq()}}), an ordination and a UMAP colored by the
levels.
\item \strong{Factor with more than \code{venn_max} levels} — same as above but the Venn
diagram is replaced by an UpSet plot (via \code{\link[=upset_pq]{upset_pq()}}), which stays
legible with many sets.
}

This is a convenience wrapper meant for quick exploration; for publication
figures, call the dedicated functions (\code{\link[=hill_bar_pq]{hill_bar_pq()}}, \code{\link[=ggscatt_pq]{ggscatt_pq()}},
\code{\link[=plot_ordination_pq]{plot_ordination_pq()}}, \code{\link[=ggvenn_pq]{ggvenn_pq()}}, \code{\link[=upset_pq]{upset_pq()}}, \code{\link[=umap_pq]{umap_pq()}}) directly to
fine-tune each panel.
}
\details{
The alpha-diversity panel relies on \pkg{patchwork} (always) and,
